As shown in Fig. 1(b), SnSe NCs exhibit a clear square outline and crystal lattice with a measured d-spacing of 3.1 Å, which is associated with the planes of SnSe. The angle between two {011} planes measured in Fig. 1(b) is 86°, which agrees with an expected calculated value of 86.42°. This suggests that the NC is viewed along the [100] zone axis. The d-spacing of the crystal plane presented in Fig. 1(c) is measured to be ∼2.9 Å and ∼3.1 Å with an angle of 90°, corresponding to the (400) and ( 01
1 ¯
) plane families of SnSe, respectively. The atomic model [Fig. 1(e–f)] is consistent with its high resolution TEM (HRTEM) image. Fig. 1(d), the as-synthesized SnSe NCs have the shape of a rectangular box, whose length equals to width but larger than height. TEM observations conducted with tilt angles of +/− 30° also confirm the cuboid-shape of SnSe NCs in Fig. S5. The NCs synthesized at 160 °C, 120 °C and 100 °C [Fig. 1(g–i)] also have a typical cuboid shape. Beside the increase in size, the shape of the formed NCs also changes with the temperature. A statistical analysis conducted on the TEM images show that NCs synthesized at higher temperature tend to have a smaller height-length ratio (Table 1 ). For example, at 200 °C, the NCs have a length/height (L/H) of 23 nm/13 nm, which is several times larger than that of L/H (9 nm/7 nm) synthesized at 100 °C (Fig. S6, and Table 1). These results unequivocally validate the 3D shape of the SnSe NCs, as well as their crystal facets and atomic orientations.
